<doc id="73341" wikidata="Q903789" url="?curid=73341" title="Disjunctive normal form">
<text>In boolean logic, a disjunctive normal form (DNF) is a canonical normal form of a logical formula consisting of a disjunction of conjunctions; it can also be described as an OR of ANDs, a sum of products, or in philosophical logic a &quot;cluster concept&quot;. As a normal form, it is useful in automated theorem proving.

==Definition==
A logical formula is considered to be in DNF if it is a disjunction of one or more conjunctions of one or more literals. A DNF formula is in full disjunctive normal form if each of its variables appears exactly once in every conjunction and each conjunction appears at most once (up to the order of variables). As in conjunctive normal form (CNF), the only propositional operators in DNF are and (formula_1), or (formula_2), and not (formula_3). The &quot;not&quot; operator can only be used as part of a literal, which means that it can only precede a propositional variable.

The following is a context-free grammar for DNF:
# &quot;DNF&quot; → (&quot;Conjunction&quot;) formula_2 &quot;DNF&quot;
# &quot;DNF&quot; → (&quot;Conjunction&quot;)
# &quot;Conjunction&quot; → &quot;Literal&quot; formula_1 &quot;Conjunction&quot;
# &quot;Conjunction&quot; → &quot;Literal&quot;
# &quot;Literal&quot; → formula_3&quot;Variable&quot;
# &quot;Literal&quot; → &quot;Variable&quot;
Where &quot;Variable&quot; is any variable.

For example, all of the following formulas are in DNF:

*formula_7
*formula_8
*formula_9
*formula_10

The formula formula_11 is in DNF, but not in full DNF; an equivalent full-DNF version is formula_12.

The following formulas are not in DNF:
*formula_13, since an OR is nested within a NOT
*formula_14, since an AND is nested within a NOT
*formula_15, since an OR is nested within an AND

==Conversion to DNF==
In classical logic each propositional formula can be converted to DNF ...

=== ... by syntactic means ===
The conversion involves using logical equivalences, such as double negation elimination, De Morgan&#x27;s laws, and the distributive law. Formulas built from the primitive connectives formula_16 can be converted to DNF by the following canonical term rewriting system:
:formula_17

=== ... by semantic means ===
The full DNF of a formula can be read off its truth table. For example, consider the formula
:formula_18.

The corresponding truth table is

* The full DNF equivalent of formula_19 is
:formula_20
* The full DNF equivalent of formula_21 is
:formula_22

=== Remark ===
A propositional formula can be represented by one and only one full DNF. In contrast, several &quot;plain&quot; DNFs may be possible. For example, by applying the rule formula_23 three times, the full DNF of the above formula_19 can be simplified to formula_25. However, there are also equivalent DNF formulas that cannot be transformed one into another by this rule, see the pictures for an example.

==Disjunctive Normal Form Theorem==
It is a theorem that all consistent formulas in propositional logic can be converted to disjunctive normal form. This is called the Disjunctive Normal Form Theorem. The formal statement is as follows:Disjunctive Normal Form Theorem: Suppose formula_26 is a sentence in a propositional language formula_27 with formula_28 sentence letters, which we shall denote by formula_29. If formula_26 is not a contradiction, then it is truth-functionally equivalent to a disjunction of conjunctions of the form formula_31, where formula_32, and formula_33.The proof follows from the procedure given above for generating DNFs from truth tables. Formally, the proof is as follows:Suppose formula_26 is a sentence in a propositional language whose sentence letters are formula_35. For each row of formula_26&#x27;s truth table, write out a corresponding conjunction formula_37, where formula_38 is defined to be formula_39 if formula_39 takes the value formula_41 at that row, and is formula_42 if formula_39 takes the value formula_44 at that row; similarly for formula_45, formula_46, etc. (the alphabetical ordering of formula_35 in the conjunctions is quite arbitrary; any other could be chosen instead). Now form the disjunction of all these conjunctions which correspond to formula_41 rows of formula_26&#x27;s truth table. This disjunction is a sentence in formula_50, which by the reasoning above is truth-functionally equivalent to formula_26. This construction obviously presupposes that formula_26 takes the value formula_41 on at least one row of its truth table; if formula_26 doesn’t, i.e., if formula_26 is a contradiction, then formula_26 is equivalent to formula_57, which is, of course, also a sentence in formula_50.This theorem is a convenient way to derive many useful metalogical results in propositional logic, such as, trivially, the result that the set of connectives formula_59 is functionally complete.

== Maximum number of conjunctions ==
Any propositional formula is built from formula_28 variables, where formula_61.

There are formula_62 possible literals: formula_63.

formula_64 has formula_65 non-empty subsets.

This is the maximum number of conjunctions a DNF can have.

A full DNF can have up to formula_66 conjunctions, one for each row of the truth table.

Example 1

Consider a formula with two variables formula_67 and formula_68.

The longest possible DNF has formula_69 conjunctions:
:formula_70

The longest possible full DNF has 4 conjunctions: they are underlined.

This formula is a tautology.

Example 2

Each DNF of the e.g. formula formula_71 has formula_72 conjunctions.

==Computational complexity==
The Boolean satisfiability problem on conjunctive normal form formulas is NP-complete. By the duality principle, so is the falsifiability problem on DNF formulas. Therefore, it is co-NP-hard to decide if a DNF formula is a tautology.

Conversely, a DNF formula is satisfiable if, and only if, one of its conjunctions is satisfiable. This can be decided in polynomial time simply by checking that at least one conjunction does not contain conflicting literals.

==Variants==
An important variation used in the study of computational complexity is &quot;k-DNF&quot;. A formula is in &quot;k-DNF&quot; if it is in DNF and each conjunction contains at most k literals.

